docs.abstract: President Trump’s discordant approach to national crises has thrust his leadership into the center of the national debate with about a week until the midterm elections.
docs.snippet: President Trump’s discordant approach to national crises has thrust his leadership into the center of the national debate with about a week until the midterm elections.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — For months, Republican officials have complained privately that President Trump lacks the ability to confront moments of crisis with moral clarity, choosing to inflame the divisions that have torn the country apart rather than try to bring it together.

headline.main: For Trump, Dutiful Words of Grief, Then Off to the Next Fight
headline.print_headline: Chief Consoler Quickly Veers Back to Attack

docs.abstract: Brad Parscale believes he is uniquely equipped to manage the potentially fractious relationships inside the campaign and sell voters on the idea of sticking with an unorthodox president.
docs.snippet: Brad Parscale believes he is uniquely equipped to manage the potentially fractious relationships inside the campaign and sell voters on the idea of sticking with an unorthodox president.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Brad Parscale, the campaign manager for President Trump’s planned re-election effort in 2020, has never run another political race of any kind. Republican establishment figures are watching him closely, in some cases quietly hoping he stumbles. And he is working for a famously mercurial boss whose 2016 campaign had three shake-ups over six months.

headline.main: Selling Donald Trump: A First-Time Campaign Manager Tries to Defy the Doubters
headline.print_headline: Selling Trump: An Untried Campaign Manager Tries to Defy the Skeptics

docs.lead_paragraph: MURPHYSBORO, Ill. — President Trump said on Saturday that “the hearts of all Americans are filled with grief” after a mass shooting at a Pittsburgh synagogue left at least 11 people dead, and he called on the country to combat hate crimes together.

docs.abstract: China’s intelligence service has used espionage and computer hackings to steal secrets from American companies to help its own government-run industries, law enforcement officials said.
docs.snippet: China’s intelligence service has used espionage and computer hackings to steal secrets from American companies to help its own government-run industries, law enforcement officials said.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Intelligence officers in a small office in China’s vast intelligence-gathering network for years stole secrets from aerospace companies in the United States and abroad, Justice Department officials said on Tuesday in unsealing the third indictment in recent weeks that detailed China’s elaborate efforts to steal corporate secrets through espionage and hacking.
